\begin_layout Section
Bushfire and heatwave weather
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires and heatwaves are dangerous natural hazards in Australia.
 In the last 100 years, heatwaves were the most hazardous natural phenomena
 for people in Australia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haynes2010"

\end_inset

.
 Bushfires ranked fourth.
 These events have also had important consequences for the Australian economy.
 Bushfires are the third most destructive natural hazard 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McAneney2009"

\end_inset

.
 These events were responsible for 20% of property losses during the period
 1900 to 2003.
 Heatwaves increase the energy demand because of the intense use of air
 conditioning systems.
 They also affect the physical integrity of civil infrastructure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pezza2011,Boschat2014,Cowan"

\end_inset

.
 The impacts produced by these events are significant for Australia.
 Therefore great effort has been devoted to understand how these events
 are produced.
 The meteorological aspects seem to link these events.
 However, in this study we show that the weather patterns of bushfire and
 heatwaves demonstrate important differences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Common variables of bushfire weather are air temperature, relative humidity,
 wind speed and rainfall.
 They are governed by large-scale weather patterns.
 These patterns have particular characteristics in different regions of
 Australia (BoM, 2009) .
 Weather patterns associated with bushfires have hot-dry air advection processes
 in common.
 Often the passage of cold fronts in bushfire areas is another characteristic.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 For example, bushfire weather in southeast Australia comprises a 'high'
 in the Tasman Sea.
 A strong cold front arriving from the west is also present (BoM, 2009).
 The passage of a cold front is associated with high winds and abrupt changes
 in wind direction.
 This can transform bushfires into extreme or even catastrophic events.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mills2005"

\end_inset

 demonstrated that a strong 850-hPa temperature gradient (associated with
 cold front arrivals) is highly correlated with extreme bushfire events
 in Victoria, Australia (see Figure 1 for location of Victoria).
 The common characteristic of bushfires and heatwaves in Victoria is the
 hot and dry environment.
 The northerly winds associated with the anticyclone in the Tasman Sea are
 linked with these conditions.
 Yet the precursors of these events can be quite different.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pezza2011"

\end_inset

demonstrated that an anticyclone (or high) in the Tasman Sea is the principal
 driver of Heatwaves in Victoria.
 In that study, heatwaves were defined as any event of three or more consecutive
 days with maximum temperatures equal to or greater than the 90th percentile
 of the monthly climatological mean.
 The minimum temperature should not drop below the 90th percentile in the
 second and third days.
 Heatwaves were associated with cyclones and anticyclones using a tracking
 scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Simmonds1999"

\end_inset

 for the period 1979-2008.
 The stability of the high in the Tasman Sea supports the dry air advection
 to southeastern Australia.
 This would prevent the passage of cold fronts, which makes this high a
 ‘blocking’ anticyclone.
 Even though there is a clear relationship between bushfires and heatwaves,
 to our knowledge these events have not been investigated in an integrated
 manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the relationship between these events, it is worth reviewing
 their connection to one of the major Australian climate drivers: El Niño
 Southern Oscillation (ENSO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Power1999,Lau2000,Risbey2009a,White2013,Klingaman2013"

\end_inset

.
 Several studies have addressed the relationship between ENSO and fire weather
 in Australia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Williams2001,Lucas2007"

\end_inset

(Williams and Karoly 1999; Verdon et al.
 2004; Lucas et al.
 2007).
 Most of these studies assert that there is a significant relationship between
 ‘El Niño’ phase of ENSO and fire weather.
 However in Victoria, fire activity is only moderately associated with ENSO
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perkins2012"

\end_inset

have suggested that ENSO phases can modulate the duration and amplitude
 of heatwaves on a global scale.
 Yet, heatwaves in southeastern Australia are not modulated by tropical
 dynamics
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pezza2011"

\end_inset

.
 This has been corroborated for heatwaves in Melbourne 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Boschat2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires occur in hot and dry conditions that generally occur during heatwaves.
 A logical train of thought would be that bushfires happen during or in
 the latter stages of a heatwaves.
 The aim of this study is to compare weather patterns of bushfires and heatwaves.
 This study considers the state of Victoria in southeast Australia during
 the period 1961-2011.
 This investigation is important because Victoria is a region affected by
 bushfires and heatwaves.
 Forecasting efforts can benefit from a deeper understanding of their synoptic
 differences.
\end_layout

